<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910605-0026</DOCNO><DOCID>910605-0026.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Microsoft Corp.:   Concern to License Software   For Multimedia Purposes</HL><DATE>06/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   MSFT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   Microsoft Corp. said it licensed software from XingTechnology Corp. that will help it combine sound, video andanimation for users of personal computers.   Xing, based in Arroyo Grande, Calif., is a leader in thefield of image compression that enables computers toefficiently store and retrieve video images. Currently, suchtasks require vast amounts of computer memory. The softwareis considered a key aspect of developing multimedia computingsystems.</LP><TEXT>   Various companies are pursuing both hardware and softwareapproaches to compressing data. Xing has &quot;the fastestsoftware-only solution we've seen,&quot; said Rob Glaser, generalmanager of Microsoft multimedia systems group. Microsoft,based in Redmond, Wash., plans to use Xing's software inconjunction with its operating systems, including Windows.   Apple Computer Inc., based in Cupertino, Calif., took astep on the multimedia front Monday by unveiling systemsoftware architecture known as QuickTime that is expected tolead to multimedia capability for its Macintosh computers.</TEXT></DOC>